Project Description: End-to-End Data Pipeline for Licensing, Violations & Payments (ADLS + Snowflake)

Blob Storage name: https://<storage-account>.dfs.core.windows.net/rawdata/raw/

https://licdatadldev01.dfs.core.windows.net/rawdata/raw/

How to get tenant id : Azure Portal → Microsoft Entra ID → Overview → Tenant ID. Snowflake’s Azure integration requires this tenant ID.

Create Snowflake Storage Integration

Use this template and replace the placeholders with your real values.

Step 1: create the integration
CREATE OR REPLACE STORAGE INTEGRATION azure_adls_int
  TYPE = EXTERNAL_STAGE
  STORAGE_PROVIDER = 'AZURE'
  ENABLED = TRUE
  AZURE_TENANT_ID = '<your-tenant-id>'
  STORAGE_ALLOWED_LOCATIONS = ('azure://<your-storage-account>.blob.core.windows.net/rawdata/raw/');

Snowflake’s Azure storage integration for external stages uses TYPE = EXTERNAL_STAGE, STORAGE_PROVIDER = 'AZURE', your Azure tenant ID, and allowed Azure locations. For Azure stages, 
Snowflake documents the azure://<account>.blob.core.windows.net/<container>/<path>/ style URL, including for ADLS Gen2-backed storage accounts.

Step 2: verify it
DESC INTEGRATION azure_adls_int;

This returns important values you need for Azure permission setup, including the generated Snowflake Azure consent URL and service principal details used to grant access on the storage side. Snowflake documents that storage integrations avoid hardcoding credentials by using a generated Azure identity.

Very important note

Even though your storage is ADLS Gen2, for the Snowflake stage and integration URL you should use the blob.core.windows.net endpoint, not the dfs.core.windows.net endpoint. Snowflake explicitly calls out using the blob endpoint for supported Azure blob storage accounts, including Data Lake Storage Gen2.

After Verfying the connection.
Authorize Snowflake in Azure
🔹 Step 1: Copy Consent URL
Copy value of: AZURE_CONSENT_URL
